                <h2 id="speaking">Speaking <a class="dm-dp-anchorLink" href="#speaking">#</a></h2>

                <p>I expected to do way less &ldquo;<a href="/speaking-podcasts/">public appearances</a>&rdquo; in 2020 because of <abbr>COVID</abbr>, but I only did 1 less thing than last year (17 in 2020 as opposed to 18 in 2019):</p>

                <ul>
                    <li>I <a href="http://www.businessology.biz/show/96/">made an appearance on The Businessology Show</a>, a podcast I helped start with Jason Blumer.</li>
                    <li>I talked to folks from <a href="https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=2676560255964391">AIGA Jacksonville</a> and <a href="https://www.facebook.com/watch/live/?v=582084159146389">the national chapter&rsquo;s portfolio review</a>, where I got to speak alongside people I admire like Lisa Babb, Ellen Lupton, and Michael Bierut.</li>
                    <li>I talked design systems <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NA5obCUoc1o">with Jina Anne</a>, for <a href="https://www.meetup.com/Ladies-That-UX-ATL/events/267834099/">Ladies that UX ATL</a>, for <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/episode-003-putting-your-components-in-context-dan/id1531717094?i=1000495559139">The Object-Oriented UX Podcast</a>, with the <a href="https://bureauofdigital.com/">Bureau of Digital</a>, at <a href="https://2020.uxpl.us/">UX+</a>, and at the <a href="https://rosenfeldmedia.com/designopssummit2020/cohorts/design-systems-and-designops/">Design Ops Summit</a>.</li>
                    <li>I talked to Marc Fonteijn twice on the Service Design Show about <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jtaPFGBnsts">pricing</a> and then again about <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJ2ppNwT6Ts">design systems for services</a>.</li>
                    <li>I emceed <a href="https://www.clarityconf.com/2020">Clarity</a>, which was my first time emceeing a conference, and I had a blast!</li>
                    <li>It&rsquo;s always a treat to doing things with local folks, so I <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/139-dan-mall/id991081339?i=1000471401603">talked to Ryan Starr at Hi-Res about my professional journey</a> and <a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/so-you-want-to-be-a-successful-ux-practitioner-registration-98794056683#">sat on a panel for PhillyCHI about being a successful UX practitioner</a>.</li>
                    <li>I talked to Alexis Collado about <a href="https://rootspodcast.design/podcast/danmall">my experience as a (half) Filipino designer</a> on his Roots podcast.</li>
                    <li>I talked to Christian Bryant about <a href="https://stackyack.tv/post/dan-mall-on-collaboration">collaboration</a> on his Stack Yack podcast.</li>
                    <li>I <a href="https://www.learnwithjason.dev/let-s-learn-design-systems">publicly taught design systems to Jason Lengstorf</a>, and he enthusiastically wrote <a href="https://www.netlify.com/tags/lets-learn-design-systems/">a 3-part series</a> about our chat!</li>
                    <li>I taught a 10-week class about design systems to seniors at Drexel University.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>I usually have a few events for the following year lined up at this point, but 2020 was weird. I&rsquo;ll be announcing a few public design system workshops shortly, so watch this space if you&rsquo;re interested.</p>


                <h2 id="work">Work <a class="dm-dp-anchorLink" href="#work">#</a></h2>

                <p>I wrote elsewhere in detail about <a href="/articles/superfriendly-2020-wrap-up/">how SuperFriendly did in 2020</a>, so suffice it to say here that I&rsquo;m extremely grateful for my SuperFriends and my clients. I&rsquo;m excited and hopeful for what we can do in 2021.</p>
                
                <p>I&rsquo;m also figuring out a way to make more impact while working less, and my family and I can <em>feel</em> it. That&rsquo;s really important to me.</p>

                <p>I co-founded <a href="https://www.usearcade.com/">Arcade</a> in 2020 with <a href="https://carbonemike.com/">Mike Carbone</a> and <a href="https://lesliecamacho.com/">Leslie Camacho</a>. It&rsquo;s the third business I&rsquo;ve ever owned/co-owned, so I guess that officially makes me an entrepreneur? We have lots of plans for Arcade in 2021, and we&rsquo;ll be sharing them on the <a href="https://log.usearcade.com/">Arcade blog</a> as we progress.</p>

                <p>There&rsquo;s also likely one more company that I&rsquo;ll hopefully be announcing this year. More on that soon.</p>


                <h2 id="#this-site">This site <a class="dm-dp-anchorLink" href="#this-site">#</a></h2>

                <p>In 2020, I published my 500th piece of content to this site, which I&rsquo;ve had for 15 years! I&rsquo;m very grateful to Past Dan&trade; for documenting so much over the years, and I really do wish I had written even more.</p>

                <p>I wrote 35 posts in 2020, which is way more than I&rsquo;ve ever posted to this site. (The last highest year was 2019 when I wrote 14 posts.) My favorites from the year were <a href="/articles/better-webcam-video/">documenting my DSLR-as-webcam setup</a> (with <a href="https://twitter.com/danmall/status/1301253596705632256">a few updates</a>), <a href="/articles/ceo-covid19-calendar/">tracking my evolving calendar blocking approach</a>, and <a href="/articles/syllabus-for-web-design-development-apprenticeships/">finally making public my syllabus for running a 9-month design or development apprenticeship</a> in case others want to try to create something like it.</p>

                <p>Of the 35 posts I wrote in 2020, 31 of them were in the new <a href="https://weeknot.es/">weeknotes</a> format I was trying out. I like this format, partly because it&rsquo;s a nice way for me to see what I do on a weekly cadence and because it gets me writing to my site more frequently. But that also reveals a problem: my <a href="/articles/">Articles</a> page is now most weeknotes, which it wasn&rsquo;t really designed for. It buries all the other posts that aren&rsquo;t weeknotes that I&rsquo;d love to highlight more. Cue the plight of all designers/developers with a personal website, especially this time of year: I want a new site.</p>

                <p>Sure, I could make a few adjustments to the design to solve the hierarchy problem, but like all sites that have been around for a while, there&rsquo;s a bunch of medium-sized things I&rsquo;ve been meaning to do. A redesign is often a good excuse to bundle all of those individual issues into an actual project. I&rsquo;m proud to have constantly iterated on this site and make small fixes over the years, but it&rsquo;s about time to do some work to make the foundation more sturdy.</p>

                <p>The other big reason for a new site is a technical one. I&rsquo;ve had free hosting from <a href="https://mediatemple.net/">MediaTemple</a> for years, ever since I met some nice MediaTemple folks at <a href="https://www.sxsw.com/">SXSW</a> one year and they offered to host my site. Then one day earlier this year, my free hosting stopped and I was suddenly on the hook to pay $100/month, which I <em>definitely</em> don&rsquo;t want to pay just to host this site. Just about all of SuperFriendly&rsquo;s work as well as <a href="https://superfriendlydesign.systems/">the site</a> is hosted on <a href="https://www.netlify.com/">Netlify</a> now, so this new hosting charge is a good catalyst for getting everything migrated. I&rsquo;m incredibly grateful for the free hosting I&rsquo;ve had for years, which is way more than I deserve, but if I&rsquo;m going to pay, I&rsquo;d rather pay for features I value like out-of-the-box SSL/TLS certificates and smart branch deploys as well as a place where all my sites can live together.</p>

                <p>Related, I&rsquo;m excited about a new <abbr title="Uniform Resource Locator">URL</abbr>. When I put up my first personal site in 2005, I used <code><a href="http://danielmall.com/">danielmall.com</a></code>, because <code>danmall.com</code> wasn&rsquo;t available. I also used the handle <code>@danielmall</code> on Twitter so I could keep my Twitter handle and personal website <abbr>URL</abbr> the same.</p>

                <p>But I&rsquo;m Dan, not Daniel. No one calls me &ldquo;Daniel&rdquo;, except for the people that don&rsquo;t really know me and assume I go by &ldquo;Daniel&rdquo; because of my <abbr>URL</abbr>.</p>

                <p>So I switched from <code>@danielmall</code> to <code>@danmall</code> on Twitter a few years ago. And I switched from <code>danielmall.com</code> to <code><a href="http://danmall.me/">danmall.me</a></code>. But I&rsquo;ve never really liked a <code>.me</code> domain for me. Feels unofficial, for some reason.</p>

                <p>I check domain registrars every so often for <code>danmall.com</code> to be available. Usually, it&rsquo;s not. But a few weeks ago, I saw it available for purchase, albeit at a pretty premium price. For most big purchases I make, I have a guideline to never decide on the spot and to always sleep on it and decide in the morning. That usually keeps my impulse purchases to a minimum. But, as a professional web designer who has waited on this domain for 15 years, I figured this didn&rsquo;t really qualify as impulsive. (Also, business expense!)</p>

                <p>So! Whenever I can get around to making it, the new version of this site is finally going to live at <code><a href="https://danmall.com/">danmall.com</a></code>! I was also thinking that I would build the site in public and even make an affordable little course about the process in case anyone&rsquo;s curious about how I design and build a site from scratch. I even have a tagline ready: &ldquo;All the boring stuff you wanted to see.&rdquo;</p>
                

                <h2 id="#miscellany">Miscellany <a class="dm-dp-anchorLink" href="#miscellany">#</a></h2>

                <ul>
                    <li>Em got <abbr>COVID</abbr> in December. It was pretty scary for a day or two, but luckily it was only that and she recovered to being good as new just in time for our move.</li>
                    <li>Joe Biden and Kamala Harris won the 2020 U.S. election! I&rsquo;m thrilled to have Trump out of office. I still haven&rsquo;t fully processed this, but I&rsquo;m hoping it means 2021 will be a much kinder year for U.S. citizens.</li>
                    <li>I&rsquo;m <em>so</em> ready for the Sixers in 2021. Ben Simmons and Joel Embiid are joined by Seth Curry, Danny Green, Dwight Howard, Tyrese Maxey, coach Doc Rivers, and more. We&rsquo;re gonna win the NBA title this year, and then we&rsquo;re going to win the Super Bowl and the Stanley Cup.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2 id="year2021">2021 <a class="dm-dp-anchorLink" href="#year2021">#</a></h2>

                <p>Goodbye, 2020. You were good, bad, and ugly.</p>

                <p>Ready for 2021.</p>

